> 🤖 **AI-generated issue** — filed automatically by the **Daily Memory Leak Hunter** agentic workflow (`[leak-scan]`). The leak below was empirically proven with a standalone `dotnet test` against the **shipped** `Microsoft.Maui.Controls` 10.0.0 package (no source build, no device) **before** filing. Please validate before acting.

## Summary

`IndicatorView` subscribes to its `ItemsSource`'s `INotifyCollectionChanged.CollectionChanged` event with a **plain (non-weak) delegate** and only unsubscribes when the `ItemsSource` property is *reassigned*. When a **shared / long-lived** collection is used as the source (the intended usage — `IndicatorView.ItemsSource` is typically bound to the same collection as a `CarouselView`), the collection keeps the `IndicatorView` (and its whole visual subtree) alive for the lifetime of that collection. Navigating away from the page does **not** clear `ItemsSource`, so nothing ever unsubscribes and the control leaks.

## Retention path

```
(shared) ObservableCollection  [long-lived root]
   └─ CollectionChanged event (strong, non-weak delegate)
        └─ IndicatorView.OnCollectionChanged   (instance method target)
             └─ IndicatorView instance  ← leaked (+ payload / visual subtree)
```

Source (`src/Controls/src/Core/IndicatorView/IndicatorView.cs`):

- Subscription (non-weak):
  - line 243–244: `if (ItemsSource is INotifyCollectionChanged collection) collection.CollectionChanged += OnCollectionChanged;`
- Unsubscription only on property change:
  - line 240–241: `if (oldItemsSource is INotifyCollectionChanged oldCollection) oldCollection.CollectionChanged -= OnCollectionChanged;` (inside `ResetItemsSource`, only invoked from the `ItemsSourceProperty` `propertyChanged` callback, line 58–59)
- Handler: `void OnCollectionChanged(object sender, ...)` line 251

There is **no** unload/teardown path (no `WeakNotifyCollectionChangedProxy`, no `Unloaded` handler) that removes the subscription when the control is detached. Compare with `ListProxy` (line 47–50) and `BindableLayout` (line 261) which both route the same kind of subscription through `WeakNotifyCollectionChangedProxy`.

## Reproduction (standalone, shipped package, plain `net10.0`)

`leakprobe.csproj`:

```xml
<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">
  <PropertyGroup>
    <TargetFramework>net10.0</TargetFramework>
    <Nullable>enable</Nullable>
    <IsPackable>false</IsPackable>
    <UseMaui>false</UseMaui>
  </PropertyGroup>
  <ItemGroup>
    <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Maui.Controls" Version="10.0.0" />
    <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk" Version="17.11.1" />
    <PackageReference Include="xunit" Version="2.9.2" />
    <PackageReference Include="xunit.runner.visualstudio" Version="2.8.2" />
  </ItemGroup>
</Project>
```

`LeakTest.cs`:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.ObjectModel;
using System.Runtime.CompilerServices;
using Microsoft.Maui.Controls;
using Xunit;

public class LeakTests
{
    const int N = 30;

    static readonly BindableProperty PayloadProperty = BindableProperty.CreateAttached(
        "Payload", typeof(byte[]), typeof(LeakTests), null);

    static void ForceGC()
    {
        for (int i = 0; i < 6; i++)
        {
            GC.Collect();
            GC.WaitForPendingFinalizers();
            GC.Collect();
        }
    }

    [MethodImpl(MethodImplOptions.NoInlining)]
    static WeakReference MakeIndicator(ObservableCollection<object> source, bool teardown)
    {
        var iv = new IndicatorView();
        iv.SetValue(PayloadProperty, new byte[1024 * 1024]); // 1 MB payload rooted by the control
        iv.ItemsSource = source;
        if (teardown)
            iv.ItemsSource = null; // ResetItemsSource(old) unsubscribes from the shared source
        return new WeakReference(iv);
    }

    [MethodImpl(MethodImplOptions.NoInlining)]
    static void Populate(ObservableCollection<object> shared,
        WeakReference[] leaky, WeakReference[] control, WeakReference[] mitigation)
    {
        for (int i = 0; i < N; i++)
            leaky[i] = MakeIndicator(shared, teardown: false);          // subscribe, never torn down
        for (int i = 0; i < N; i++)
            control[i] = MakeIndicator(new ObservableCollection<object>(), teardown: false); // private source
        for (int i = 0; i < N; i++)
            mitigation[i] = MakeIndicator(shared, teardown: true);      // subscribe then clear
    }

    [Fact]
    public void IndicatorView_ItemsSource_Leaks()
    {
        var sharedSource = new ObservableCollection<object>(); // long-lived root

        var leaky = new WeakReference[N];
        var control = new WeakReference[N];
        var mitigation = new WeakReference[N];

        Populate(sharedSource, leaky, control, mitigation);

        ForceGC();

        int leakyAlive = 0, controlAlive = 0, mitigationAlive = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < N; i++)
        {
            if (leaky[i].IsAlive) leakyAlive++;
            if (control[i].IsAlive) controlAlive++;
            if (mitigation[i].IsAlive) mitigationAlive++;
        }

        GC.KeepAlive(sharedSource);

        Assert.Equal(N, leakyAlive);
        Assert.Equal(0, controlAlive);
        Assert.Equal(0, mitigationAlive);
    }
}
```

Run:

```bash
dotnet test --logger "console;verbosity=normal"
```

## Observed results

| Scenario | Description | Alive after GC (N=30) | Retained |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Leaky** | shared source, no teardown | **30 / 30** | ~30 MB |
| **Control** | private source that dies with the control | 0 / 30 | 0 |
| **Mitigation** | shared source, `ItemsSource = null` on teardown | 0 / 30 | 0 |

`Test Run Successful` → the leaky path retains all 30 controls while both the Control and Mitigation paths fully release, empirically confirming the leak and the mechanism.

## Affected platforms

All platforms — this is purely-managed cross-platform code in `Microsoft.Maui.Controls` (`src/Controls/src/Core/IndicatorView/IndicatorView.cs`). No default/opt-in condition is required; the leak occurs whenever `IndicatorView.ItemsSource` is bound to a collection that outlives the control (the documented, intended usage of pairing it with a `CarouselView`'s source).

## Suggested fix

Route the `CollectionChanged` subscription through a weak proxy — e.g. `WeakNotifyCollectionChangedProxy` — exactly as `ListProxy` (`src/Controls/src/Core/ListProxy.cs:47-50`) and `BindableLayout` (`src/Controls/src/Core/BindableLayout/BindableLayout.cs:261`) already do, so the shared source no longer strongly roots the `IndicatorView`. Alternatively (or additionally) unsubscribe on `Unloaded`/handler-disconnect.

## Scope note

This is a genuine framework retention bug, not just a usage footgun: the control's own documentation steers users toward binding `ItemsSource` to a shared, long-lived collection, and the framework offers no teardown hook that fires on navigation-away. The repo already has the `WeakNotifyCollectionChangedProxy` primitive used for the identical pattern elsewhere, so the fix is low-risk and consistent with existing conventions.




