## Summary

`ListView` subscribes to `RefreshCommand.CanExecuteChanged` with a **plain (non-weak) delegate** and only unsubscribes when the `RefreshCommand` property changes. When a `ListView` is bound to a `RefreshCommand` owned by a longer-lived source and the `ListView` is then detached/navigated-away **without** the command being cleared, the command keeps the entire `ListView` alive.

(`ListView` is deprecated in favor of `CollectionView`, but it still ships and is widely used, and the raw subscription is a real managed leak.) MAUI hardens the same pattern elsewhere via `WeakCommandSubscription`.

## Retention path

`ICommand (long-lived) -> CanExecuteChanged delegate -> ListView.OnCommandCanExecuteChanged -> ListView -> cell/template subtree`

Citations (repo `src/Controls/src/Core/ListView/ListView.cs`):
- Line 771 — `newCommand.CanExecuteChanged += OnCommandCanExecuteChanged;` (strong subscribe in `OnRefreshCommandChanged`)
- Lines 762–778 — the handler is only removed when the `RefreshCommand` value changes; there is no unload/teardown hook.

## Observed results

| Scenario | Alive (of 30) | Retained |
|----------|--------------:|---------:|
| Control (no RefreshCommand assigned) | 0 | ~0 MB |
| Mitigation (RefreshCommand set to null before discard) | 0 | ~0 MB |
| **Leaky (RefreshCommand left assigned, ListView detached)** | **30** | **~30 MB** |

## Affected platforms

Purely managed cross-platform code (`src/Controls/src/Core`) → **all platforms**.

## Suggested fix

Use `WeakCommandSubscription` for the `RefreshCommand.CanExecuteChanged` subscription, or unsubscribe on handler-disconnect / unload.

**Scope note:** Framework-hardenable managed leak. Binding `RefreshCommand` to a view-model command is the documented pull-to-refresh pattern, and users have no unload hook to null it, so a weak subscription is appropriate.

### Standalone repro (shipped package, plain `net10.0`, no device)

The single project below confirms all three ICommand `CanExecuteChanged` leaks in one `dotnet test` run. Each `[Fact]` allocates 30 controls each owning a 1 MB payload, tracked by `WeakReference`, then forces a full GC.

